name: 1,2,3-Trimethylbenzene
Reason: The basic unit for 1,2,3-trimethylbenzene is benzene which has a melting point of 5.5 °C. The presence of methyl groups typically lowers the melting point due to disruption of the crystal lattice and increased steric hindrance between molecules which makes the packing less efficient and thus easier to break apart (melt). Each methyl group is predicted to lower the melting point. For toluene, which has one methyl group, the melting point is -95 °C. The decrease from benzene to toluene due to one methyl group is -100.5 °C. With three methyl groups, it is reasonable to predict that each additional methyl group will further lower the melting point, but the effect of additional groups may not be strictly additive due to steric hindrance and the limit to how much these groups can disrupt crystal packing. We will estimate the effect of each methyl group beyond the first to be somewhat less, say around -70 °C.
